Certainly! Below is a simple HTML5 implementation of a 4x4 grid that displays a white skeleton running on a black background. Each cell of the grid represents a frame of the animation. For this example, I'll use a simple placeholder animation with basic CSS transitions since animating a skeleton requires specific asset frames, which are not included here. You can replace the placeholder frames with actual images of a skeleton if you have them.

Here is the complete code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Skeleton Animation</title>
    <style>
        body {
            background-color: black;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
        }
        .grid {
            display: grid;
            grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 100px);
            grid-template-rows: repeat(4, 100px);
            gap: 5px;
        }
        .cell {
            width: 100px;
            height: 100px;
            background-color: black;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            border: 1px solid white;  /* Just for better visibility */
        }
        .skeleton {
            width: 80%;  /* Adjust as necessary */
            height: 80%; /* Adjust as necessary */
            animation: run 1s steps(4) infinite; /* Adjust timing and steps as necessary */
        }
        @keyframes run {
            0% { background-position: 0; }
            100% { background-position: -400px; } /* Update based on your actual frame width */
        }
        /* Create placeholders for the skeleton frames */
        .frame1 { background-image: url('frame1.png'); }
        .frame2 { background-image: url('frame2.png'); }
        .frame3 { background-image: url('frame3.png'); }
        .frame4 { background-image: url('frame4.png'); }
        .frame5 { background-image: url('frame5.png'); }
        .frame6 { background-image: url('frame6.png'); }
        .frame7 { background-image: url('frame7.png'); }
        .frame8 { background-image: url('frame8.png'); }
        /* Add as many frames as necessary */
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="grid">
        <div class="cell frame1"></div>
        <div class="cell frame2"></div>
        <div class="cell frame3"></div>
        <div class="cell frame4"></div>
        <div class="cell frame5"></div>
        <div class="cell frame6"></div>
        <div class="cell frame7"></div>
        <div class="cell frame8"></div>
        <!-- Add more cells as needed -->
    </div>
    <script>
        // JavaScript can be used to enhance functionality if needed
        // For example, you could add event listeners, etc.
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Key Points:
1. **Background Color**: The body has a black background to contrast with the white skeleton.
2. **Grid Layout**: A CSS Grid Layout is used to organize the cells.
3. **Animated Frames**: You can replace the `background-image` URLs with actual images of frames of a skeleton running.
4. **Animation Effect**: A simple CSS animation is created. The `@keyframes` specifies the movement across the frames. Adjust it based on actual frame sizes.

### Note:
Replace the placeholder URLs for the frame images (`frame1.png`, `frame2.png`, etc.) with the actual paths to your skeleton animation images. The animation will work by moving the background position across the different frames in a sequence. Adjust the grid size, frame counts, and animation duration based on your specific assets and requirements.
